- Whoever they are.
- Oh, shit! Ooh. I'm sorry, I'm sorry.

36:17.560 --> 36:21.102
Earlier today, I watched
as a woman from the village

36:21.185 --> 36:23.143
desperately tried to save her own child,

36:23.227 --> 36:26.143
feverishly wiping the blood
off the pavement

36:26.227 --> 36:29.143
<i>as if that would somehow bring him back.</i>

36:29.227 --> 36:33.560
A peasant, a fat, sweaty peasant,
looked on,

36:33.643 --> 36:39.518
useless, hopeless, worthless even,
knowing that nothing he ever did

36:39.602 --> 36:41.977
could possibly do any good.

36:42.060 --> 36:43.977
This is Frank Bonneville,
live from Machala.

36:46.435 --> 36:49.268
- Good work.
- You're on again at 7:00, call back.

36:50.852 --> 36:55.102
- That's why he's the best.
- I hope they're being careful.

36:59.143 --> 37:01.018
Well, we got away with it again.

37:10.518 --> 37:12.060
Looks like we made quite an impact.

37:23.727 --> 37:26.407
- I'm not sure about this.
- We can't stay in the apartment all day.

37:26.435 --> 37:28.268
We need some fresh air,
some exercise.

37:28.352 --> 37:31.310
I know, but what if we're spotted?
Game over, isn't it?

37:31.393 --> 37:33.560
Oh, wow. Look. Oh.

37:34.602 --> 37:36.268
<i>Amazing Spider-Man</i> 14.

37:37.185 --> 37:39.560
I collect comics,
so I know that's a good one.

37:39.643 --> 37:41.685
Yeah, we really should get back.
Come on.

37:48.435 --> 37:50.643
- It's Mallard.
- Shit. Don't answer it.

37:50.727 --> 37:52.810
I've gotta answer it. Hi.

37:53.560 --> 37:58.727
It's Finch. He's in the toilet. Yeah.

37:59.518 --> 38:03.935
I don't know where we are, exactly.
It's all written in Spanish, obviously.

38:04.018 --> 38:06.185
So... That's the subway.

38:07.268 --> 38:10.393
That's what we call the trucks
that drive the tanks.

38:10.477 --> 38:14.768
Yeah, because it sounds like the subway.
Okay, yeah, I'll let him know.

38:16.393 --> 38:18.977
- He wants you to do a report at 1:00.
- Shit.

38:19.060 --> 38:20.352
- He's onto us, man.
- He's...

38:22.560 --> 38:27.060
Hi. Yeah, he's out. Okay, hold on.

38:28.143 --> 38:30.518
- Hello?
- I just need a 60-second update, Frank,

38:30.602 --> 38:32.643
and then, uh,
we'll trail something bigger.

38:32.727 --> 38:34.435
- Here?
<i>- What do you mean, "Here"?</i>

38:34.518 --> 38:37.560
- I mean, now?
- Yes, yes. We're transferring you.

38:37.643 --> 38:40.393
Now we go live
to Frank Bonneville in Ecuador.

38:40.477 --> 38:43.518
A cloud of dust rises into the horizon.

38:44.602 --> 38:47.810
The silence is broken by the
caterpillar tracks of two rogue tanks...

38:49.143 --> 38:52.018
...whose tracks are biting
into the dust on the remote road.

38:52.102 --> 38:53.893
<i>A helicopter hovers overhead.</i>

38:57.143 --> 38:59.852
- Is this Dr. Schmalzstein's office?
- No. Shh.

39:00.393 --> 39:02.852
In the bombed-out remains
of what was once his home,

39:02.935 --> 39:04.175
a young boy watches television.

39:04.227 --> 39:07.060
Blow it out your ass!

39:07.227 --> 39:10.602
American television.
Shells are incoming.

39:12.393 --> 39:17.102
My technician is hit by shrapnel.
Oh, no, he's fine.

39:17.185 --> 39:19.102
But we gotta get out of here. Fast.

39:37.435 --> 39:40.685
It's quiet. Too quiet, if anything.

39:43.935 --> 39:49.518
In the sky, a combat helicopter stops.
An explosion rings out.

39:49.602 --> 39:51.977
My own technician
has another near miss.

39:52.435 --> 39:54.977
A bullet flies inches above his head.

39:55.893 --> 40:00.352
Luckily for him, he's so short,
or he'd most certainly be dead by now.

40:00.435 --> 40:03.227
This is Frank Bonneville, Q365 News.

40:03.310 --> 40:05.768
Coming up at 7:00,
we will have another exclusive

40:05.852 --> 40:07.352
from Frank Bonneville.

40:07.435 --> 40:10.518
That was too close for comfort.
We can't get caught out like this again.

40:10.602 --> 40:14.102
We've gotta plan this, be in control.
And we need something new.

40:14.185 --> 40:18.018
When Mallard first asked you to go
to Ecuador, what did he say, exactly?

40:18.102 --> 40:20.893
Just that the rebel forces
were amassing arms, weapons.

40:20.977 --> 40:23.185
- What else?
- Conjecture, rumors.

40:23.268 --> 40:26.477
That's enough for you, though,
isn't it? Anything that sells news.

40:26.560 --> 40:30.185
- Well, if people weren't so gullible...
- That's it.

40:30.268 --> 40:31.727
- What?
- We start a rumor.

40:31.852 --> 40:35.602
One that can't be proved wrong. We invent
someone, someone behind all this.

40:35.685 --> 40:38.977
And when people say,
"Oh, we can't find this guy, who is he?"

40:39.060 --> 40:42.477
"Well, no, of course you can't find him.
He's elusive. He's an evil genius.

40:42.560 --> 40:46.810
He's protected by a loyal army.
He can work for anyone.

40:46.935 --> 40:48.227
Be funded by anyone."

40:49.768 --> 40:51.408
They'll just deny it, though, won't they?

40:51.477 --> 40:55.143
So, the headline would read
"So-and-so denies funding terrorists."

40:55.268 --> 40:57.227
- Great.
- That's unethical, though.

40:57.352 --> 41:01.018
Yeah, but it's news.
What's a popular Spanish name?

41:02.060 --> 41:06.477
Alvarez. Santiago. Emilio.

41:07.060 --> 41:11.102
The man is Emilio Santiago Alvarez,

41:11.185 --> 41:14.893
the instigator of the attacks against
government forces in Ecuador.

41:16.102 --> 41:20.518
A small man, with no profile,
no international presence.

41:21.685 --> 41:25.852
But here, in the jungles and towns
of southern Ecuador,

41:25.935 --> 41:27.393
he's become a folk hero...

41:27.935 --> 41:30.810
a man unafraid to stand up
and be counted.

41:31.685 --> 41:36.018
<i>But on the street, rumors persist
that Alvarez may not be working alone.</i>

41:37.227 --> 41:41.893
His rebel forces are too well equipped,
too well trained, too well fed.

41:43.143 --> 41:47.602
It's said, and I must stress at this
point, these rumors are uncorroborated...

41:48.268 --> 41:51.935
that maybe Alvarez
has friends in high places.

41:52.018 --> 41:54.518
Perhaps a little too close to home.

41:54.643 --> 41:58.727
Jesus, is he saying that the rebel forces
are being funded by the U.S.?

41:58.810 --> 42:01.102
<i>This is Frank Bonneville, Q365 News.</i>

42:01.185 --> 42:02.602
That's huge.

42:03.352 --> 42:05.518
Good one.
Couldn't have done better myself.

42:06.602 --> 42:10.018
- We can keep this going for ages.
- Yeah, let's see if they buy it first.

42:10.102 --> 42:12.227
They will.

42:13.018 --> 42:14.143
They will.

42:14.935 --> 42:17.435
Does Bonneville
realize the mess he's made

42:17.518 --> 42:21.143
by allowing speculation that this Alvarez
is working for the Americans?

42:21.268 --> 42:23.352
Most probably, Madam Secretary.

42:24.602 --> 42:28.852
Goddamn it. Why have we not heard of this
man before? Where's your intelligence?

42:28.977 --> 42:32.143
Our agents in Ecuador are tracing him now.

42:32.685 --> 42:36.060
It's a good chance they know him
by another name. A nickname.

42:36.643 --> 42:39.477
And if they don't find him,
government forces will.

42:39.560 --> 42:43.102
They're now looking for Bonneville
to make him confess his sources.

42:43.227 --> 42:47.435
And Alvarez's men are after him
because he revealed too much.

42:47.518 --> 42:50.268
He and his technician
are in serious danger.

42:50.352 --> 42:54.393
I do not wanna end up with two dead
citizens nor the wrath of their families.

42:55.602 --> 42:59.352
You are going to tell Finch and Bonneville
to get to the American embassy in Quito

42:59.435 --> 43:02.643
as soon as possible.
We need to know they're safe.

43:02.727 --> 43:05.018
Once they're safe, we will extract them.

43:05.518 --> 43:07.352
That is something we know how to do.

43:07.435 --> 43:10.227
<i>Little is known about the mastermind
behind the uprising,</i>

43:10.310 --> 43:12.727
<i>rebel fighter Emilio Alvarez.</i>

43:12.810 --> 43:15.518
<i>The charismatic leader
of the Ecuadorian Liberation Front</i>

43:15.602 --> 43:17.643
<i>is believed to come
from humble beginnings.</i>

43:17.727 --> 43:18.893
<i>The son of an unemployed,</i>

43:18.977 --> 43:23.602
<i>left-wing atheist father and an unmarried
mother with Communist sympathies.</i>

43:23.685 --> 43:27.977
<i>So, in your view, Alvarez has been quietly
amassing a force for some time now.</i>

43:28.060 --> 43:30.810
<i>What I'm hearing from my sources
is that Alvarez has risen</i>

43:30.893 --> 43:34.310
<i>to a position of power in the Ecuadorian
Liberation Front for some years.</i>

43:34.435 --> 43:36.560
I always knew he made up
most of the shit he reported.

43:36.643 --> 43:38.227
<i>So, why haven't we heard of him before?</i>

43:38.810 --> 43:42.310
<i>- Well, it makes perfect sense.</i>
- How is he keeping a straight face?

43:42.435 --> 43:44.435
<i>...less chance for the opposition
of targeting you.</i>

43:45.060 --> 43:48.018
<i>Successful revolution is all about
protecting your leaders.</i>

43:48.102 --> 43:51.310
<i>So, Frank Bonneville has gone where
no other news reporter has gone before</i>

43:51.393 --> 43:53.233
<i>in bringing this man
to the public's attention.</i>

43:53.310 --> 43:55.143
<i>I wouldn't say that.</i>

43:55.227 --> 43:57.393
<i>I've known about Alvarez myself
for a while now.</i>

43:57.477 --> 43:59.727
<i>I just didn't think it was appropriate
to unmask him yet.</i>

43:59.852 --> 44:01.810
Oh, come on.

44:01.893 --> 44:03.935
Oh.

44:14.685 --> 44:17.727
Hello? Yeah.

44:20.310 --> 44:21.310
Right.

44:24.143 --> 44:25.518
Uh-huh.

44:27.393 --> 44:28.518
What?

44:29.852 --> 44:32.018
Okay. Yeah, sure.

44:32.602 --> 44:34.643
Yeah, I'll call you
as soon as we get to Quito.

44:36.102 --> 44:37.102
Okay, thanks.

44:38.310 --> 44:39.352
- We're screwed.
- Why?

44:39.435 --> 44:42.018
- Everyone's looking for us, apparently.
- They won't find us.

44:42.143 --> 44:43.823
Of course they won't,
that's not the point.

44:43.852 --> 44:45.685
- What is?
- Mallard wants us to get to

44:45.768 --> 44:48.060
the U.S. embassy in Quito immediately.

44:48.143 --> 44:51.185
For our own safety.
The ambassador's waiting for us, okay?

44:51.268 --> 44:54.352
It's probably a few hours' drive
from Machala to Quito.

44:54.435 --> 44:56.435
I promised I'd call him
as soon as we got there.

44:56.518 --> 44:58.643
- As in, a few hours from now.
- Right.

45:00.143 --> 45:01.935
- What are you gonna do?
- Nothing.

45:02.935 --> 45:04.575
- Because I'm not gonna call him.
- Why not?

45:04.643 --> 45:08.935
Because if I call him, he'll call the
embassy to arrange us to be flown home,

45:09.060 --> 45:12.602
- and they'll say we're not there. Right?
- Right. Yeah.

45:12.727 --> 45:14.727
What will he think
if you don't call him at all?

45:15.310 --> 45:17.560
- That something's happened to us.
- We're just missing?

45:17.685 --> 45:20.143
Yeah, that we're missing.
They can trace us, though.

45:20.227 --> 45:22.393
That's what they'd do
if they thought we were missing.

45:23.393 --> 45:27.310
- So, we'd have to destroy our phones.
- We only have to destroy the SIM card.

45:27.393 --> 45:29.310
- Right.
- Oh, God.

45:31.977 --> 45:33.977
How can you destroy it? It doesn't...

45:34.060 --> 45:36.268
You can't even...
Shall I just swallow it?

45:36.352 --> 45:38.935
Yeah, swallow it so they can trace it
straight to your ass!

45:39.018 --> 45:41.338
Why didn't we just go back
in the first place and just say:

45:41.393 --> 45:43.018
"Sorry, we threw away the tickets
and passports"?

45:43.143 --> 45:46.310
Why did you throw the fucking ticket
and the passport away in the first place?

45:46.393 --> 45:48.560
- That's the fucking question!
- Shut up!

45:48.643 --> 45:50.683
What will they think
we're arguing about downstairs?

45:50.768 --> 45:52.602
- I don't care!
- Are you mental?

45:53.435 --> 45:57.143
Fucking hell.
There. It's destroyed, okay?

45:58.643 --> 46:01.243
What are they gonna say,
"What were you arguing about last night?"

46:01.310 --> 46:03.102
In their house.

46:04.685 --> 46:06.602
You're such a pig.

46:06.685 --> 46:09.310
We haven't heard from them
since 10:00 last night.

46:09.393 --> 46:11.893
Maybe they lost communication,
maybe they've been arrested.

46:11.977 --> 46:15.977
Whatever the case, we need to
be very quiet about this for now.

46:16.060 --> 46:18.643
All right, drop everything,
check the hotels, hospitals,

46:18.727 --> 46:21.060
anybody we might know in the area
who might have seen them.

46:21.143 --> 46:23.103
And at some point,
we have to let Ian's wife know.

46:23.477 --> 46:25.060
- Leave it with me.
- Okay.

46:25.143 --> 46:27.310
I need a map of Ecuador, ASAP.

46:27.393 --> 46:30.518
- Got it.
- Q365 News. Hold on.

46:30.602 --> 46:32.310
It's Barrymore at the <i>New York Post.</i>

46:32.393 --> 46:33.852
<i>There's that little guy.</i>

46:33.935 --> 46:36.560
Okay, Barrymore, I gotta tell you,
I don't have time. What?

46:36.643 --> 46:40.393
I know you've got a big problem.
I just spoke to my correspondent in Quito.

46:40.518 --> 46:42.238
I don't know anything.
I can't say anything.

46:42.268 --> 46:45.227
I need photos for a profile piece.
Should I send a courier?

46:45.810 --> 46:48.560
- Being a bit hasty, aren't you?
- <i>If I know about it</i>

46:48.643 --> 46:50.602
then other people do, too,
and it'll get out.

46:50.685 --> 46:51.935
Send your courier.

46:52.477 --> 46:56.477
Okay, story's out. Change of plans.
You're going on at 7:00.

46:56.602 --> 47:00.435
Just say we've lost contact
with our special correspondents in Ecuador

47:00.518 --> 47:02.977
- but let's not panic everyone.
- Right.

47:03.060 --> 47:04.768
- You got this.
- Yeah.

47:04.852 --> 47:05.852
Okay.

47:08.602 --> 47:09.643
Oh, hold on.

47:11.268 --> 47:12.935
Excuse me, have you got <i>PC Gamer?</i>

47:13.810 --> 47:15.102
Look. Look.

47:16.602 --> 47:19.060
And uh, and the <i>New York Post.</i>

47:20.393 --> 47:22.393
Thanks. Cheers.

47:30.352 --> 47:34.143
- Do you want a drink?
- Uh, no, I'm fine. Thank you.

47:39.060 --> 47:42.810
You know,
when you're in broadcasting...

47:44.018 --> 47:48.060
any number of things can happen,
but they aren't necessarily serious.

47:48.893 --> 47:53.018
If that's the case,
then they're gonna call any minute now.

48:00.477 --> 48:01.685
Do you know Frank well?

48:03.852 --> 48:05.477
Uh, Frank?

48:07.185 --> 48:10.518
We've been working together
for about five years.

48:11.310 --> 48:13.977
He's a great journalist.

48:14.685 --> 48:18.518
Bit of a loner. But I've been
working with Ian even longer.

48:20.352 --> 48:22.393
He's such a kind soul.

48:23.393 --> 48:25.935
- You must be worried sick.
- Yeah.

48:31.143 --> 48:32.227
What do you mean, "loner"?

48:34.810 --> 48:36.060
Uh...

48:37.685 --> 48:43.352
Well... you know what?
Actually, I could do with a drink.

48:50.018 --> 48:51.852
Aren't you gonna record
our conversation?

48:51.935 --> 48:55.060
Oh, no. This is strictly off the record.

48:55.143 --> 48:58.810
Because I tell you,
it is a very interesting story.

48:59.393 --> 49:01.768
My life, before I met Ian.

49:04.727 --> 49:07.560
- Before? Yeah.
- Yeah, you know, special interest.

49:07.643 --> 49:10.602
Because it might make people
engage with their plight even more.

49:10.685 --> 49:13.810
Well, maybe next time.

49:13.893 --> 49:17.102
I don't wanna add to your... stress.

49:18.268 --> 49:21.727
I mean, sometimes I think
that my life has been too dramatic.

49:22.477 --> 49:28.268
And I almost wish it was more, like, uh...
plain and boring.

49:28.352 --> 49:30.060
Well...

49:30.143 --> 49:33.935
- I should go. Sorry. I'm so sorry.
- Clumsy.

49:41.477 --> 49:44.935
<i>Nothing yet leads us
to give in to anxiety,</i>

49:45.018 --> 49:49.518
<i>even if foreign journalists today
incur increasingly real risks.</i>

49:49.602 --> 49:53.018
<i>Thank you, Claire Maddox.
And coming up next, baseball.</i>

49:53.977 --> 49:57.560
If you don't get in touch at all,
they're going to think you're dead.

49:59.518 --> 50:03.143
- Or taken hostage, or, yeah.
- Taken hostage?

50:04.393 --> 50:07.935
- Yeah.
- We're taken hostage.

50:10.268 --> 50:13.102
- What do you mean?
- If we can fake being in Ecuador,

50:13.185 --> 50:15.435
- we can fake being taken hostage.
- That's bad.

50:15.518 --> 50:18.268
- That's not a good idea.
- It's not bad, it's genius.

50:18.352 --> 50:19.393
You're a genius.

50:19.477 --> 50:21.102
- Am I?
- Yeah.

50:21.185 --> 50:23.393
- He's a genius.
- He is a smart man.

50:23.477 --> 50:24.477
Nah.

50:24.560 --> 50:27.102
- It's a very good idea.
- Is it?

50:27.727 --> 50:28.893
I don't know.

50:31.018 --> 50:33.418
- Baby, you're blocking Ian.
- Oh, sorry.

50:33.477 --> 50:35.893
- Okay. Okay.
- Okay.

50:35.977 --> 50:37.060
It's recording.

50:38.643 --> 50:40.727
- And...
- Wait, wait, wait!

50:41.352 --> 50:42.352
- Okay.
- Okay.

50:42.393 --> 50:43.393
Ready?

50:43.810 --> 50:44.852
- Yeah.
- Okay.

50:47.310 --> 50:48.602
Hello.

50:48.685 --> 50:51.518
Don't smile and say "hello."
For God's sake.

50:51.602 --> 50:53.402
- What do you mean?
- You're in mortal danger.

50:53.477 --> 50:55.977
You got two guys that wanna kill you.
Are they high heels?

50:56.060 --> 50:59.268
- What rebel soldier wears high heels?
- They make my legs look longer.

50:59.352 --> 51:02.102
- It looks good, baby.
- Thank you, baby.

51:02.185 --> 51:05.102
Okay, no smiling. No hello.
Just straight to it.

51:08.143 --> 51:11.935
We are hostages
of the Ecuadorian Liberation Front.

51:12.018 --> 51:16.143
Um, and I am talking to the
president of the United States here

51:16.227 --> 51:18.477
when I say the situation is simple.

51:18.560 --> 51:20.643
If you do not pay the ransom,
we will be executed.

51:20.727 --> 51:21.727
- Stop. Okay.
- What?

51:21.768 --> 51:24.060
Why are you talking so casually,
so nonchalant?

51:24.143 --> 51:26.477
You gotta be begging.
Begging for your life.

51:26.560 --> 51:27.935
This guy, he wants to kill you.

51:28.018 --> 51:30.143
He wants to stick you like a pig,
so you need to beg.

51:30.227 --> 51:32.852
- A nice word to your family, to your wife.
- Yeah.

51:32.935 --> 51:35.102
The lens?
That's the whole world, right there.

51:35.185 --> 51:36.393
- You gotta connect.
- Yeah.

51:36.477 --> 51:38.393
- Do you understand?
- Yeah, yeah, yeah. Okay.

51:39.018 --> 51:40.102
President.

51:40.185 --> 51:43.727
Beg the president, mention the family,
yeah, yeah, yeah. Okay.

51:45.060 --> 51:46.060
No smiling.

51:51.727 --> 51:55.268
We are hostages of
the Ecuadorian Liberation Front,

51:55.352 --> 51:58.810
and I beg you, Mr. President,
please help us.

51:59.477 --> 52:03.352
Also, uh, tell my family I love them,
tell my wife...

52:03.435 --> 52:06.227
Why are you asking the president
to run errands for you?

52:06.310 --> 52:10.477
- Ugh. I don't know, I just... You said...
- Talk to them directly, to the lens.

52:11.560 --> 52:14.768
- Dear Mr. President, wife, family...
- Stop.

52:14.852 --> 52:16.393
- Get up.
- What?

52:19.310 --> 52:21.810
- Okay. Shake it out.
- Oh!

52:21.893 --> 52:24.810
- Take that, American pig!
- That wasn't part of the video.

52:24.893 --> 52:26.933
- What was that for?
- To help you get into your role.

52:26.977 --> 52:29.810
Who am I? Daniel Day-Fucking-Lewis?
Why am I doing this

52:29.893 --> 52:32.893
- if you're the charismatic broadcaster?
- Exactly. I can't do it.

52:32.977 --> 52:34.435
No one's gonna feel sorry for me.

52:34.518 --> 52:37.518
I got the looks, I got the charm,
I got the body. No sympathy.

52:37.602 --> 52:41.477
You, on the other hand,
you begging for your life? It's pathetic.

52:41.560 --> 52:44.518
It's like an ugly runt, mongrel dog
that no one wants,

52:44.602 --> 52:46.602
- that has to be put down.
- Yeah, I get the point.

52:48.852 --> 52:50.477
Didn't have to hit me.

52:52.518 --> 52:54.185
